  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and expectations for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases\n- Facilitate information sharing and evidence collection across borders\n- Enable extradition of individuals involved in financial crimes\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Encourage consistent legal frameworks\n- Develop common definitions of money laundering\n- Standardize reporting and compliance requirements\n- Promote international banking transparency\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Financial institutions required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) protocols\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Cross-border transaction monitoring\n\n5. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International sanctions against countries with weak AML regulations\n- Coordinated actions against financial networks\n- Shared intelligence and investigative resources\n\n6. Technology and Information Exchange\n- Digital platforms for financial intelligence\n- Collaborative databases\n- Real-time tracking of suspicious financial activities\n\nThese intersections help create a comprehensive global approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering.",
